Let (S \triangleright  P, \iota ^S, \otimes ^S, \text {pr}^S) and (T \triangleright  Q, \iota ^T, \otimes ^T, \text {pr}^T) be lmf-containers. We define their direct composite as the lmf-container (S \triangleright  P \circ  T \triangleright  Q, \iota , \otimes , \text {pr}) where

       \begin {align*}            \iota  &:= (\iota ^S , \lambda  \_ . \iota ^T)\\     (s , f) \otimes  (s' , f') &:= (s \otimes ^S s' , \lambda  p . f\ (\text {pr}^S_1\ p) \otimes ^T f'\ (\text {pr}^S_2\ p))\\     \text {pr}\ (p , q) &:= ((\text {pr}^S_1\ p , \text {pr}^T_1\ q) , (\text {pr}^S_2\ p , \text {pr}^T_2\ q))        \end {align*}   

  This is a generalisation of the direct product of monoids.

We define the composite monad container (see composite container) (S \triangleright  P \circ  T \triangleright  Q, \iota , \sigma , \text {pr}) where

       \begin {align*}            \iota  &:= (\iota ^S , \lambda  \_ . \iota ^T)\\     \sigma \ (s , f)\ g &:= (\\       &\sigma ^S\ s\ (\lambda  p . u_1\ (f\ p)\ (g_1\ p)) ,\\       &\lambda  p . \sigma ^T\          (u_2\ (f\ (\text {pr}^S_1\ p))\ (g_1\ (\text {pr}^S_1\ p))\ (\text {pr}^S_2\ p))\          (\lambda  q . g_2\ (\text {pr}^S_1\ p)\ (v_1\ (\text {pr}^S_2\ p)\ q)\ (v_2\ (\text {pr}^S_2\ p)\ q))\\     &)\\     \text {pr}\ (p, q) &:= (\\     &(\text {pr}^S_1\ p , v_1\ (\text {pr}^S_2\ p)\ (\text {pr}^T_1\ q)),\\      &(v_2\ (\text {pr}^S_2\ p)\ (\text {pr}^T_1\ q) , \text {pr}^T_2\ q)\\     &)        \end {align*}   

  where g_i := \pi _i \circ  g. The equations for this monad container hold given the equations for the two constituant monad containers and the distributive law.

Let (1 \triangleright  \lambda  \_ . A, \downarrow ^A, o^A, \oplus ^A) and (1 \triangleright  \lambda  \_ . B, \downarrow ^B, o^B, \oplus ^B) be representable directed containers. By specialising the equations of a directed container distributive law to these, all equations involving u_2 disappear and we are left with:
       \begin {align*}       v_1\ b\ o^A &= o^A\\       v_1\ o^B\ a &= a\\       v_1\ b\ (a \oplus ^A a') &= v_1\ b\ a \oplus ^A v_1\ (v_2\ b\ a)\ a'\\       v_1\ (b \oplus ^B b')\ a &= v_1\ b\ (v_1\ b'\ a)\\       v_2\ b\ o^A &= b\\       v_2\ o^B\ a &= o^B\\       v_2\ b\ (a \oplus ^A a') &= v_2\ (v_2\ b\ a)\ a'\\       v_2\ (b \oplus ^B b')\ a &= v_2\ b\ (v_1\ b' a) \oplus ^B v_2\ b'\ a     \end {align*}   
  which exhibit v_1 and v_2 as a matching pair of monoid maps between the monoids (A , o^A, \oplus ^A) and (B, o^B, \oplus ^B). Hence, directed container distributive laws of this type are in bijection with matching pairs of actions for the relevant monoids.

Let (A \triangleright  \lambda  \_ . 1, \iota ^A, \sigma ^A, \text {pr}^A) and (B \triangleright  \lambda  \_ . 1, \iota ^B, \sigma ^B, \text {pr}^B) be monad containers. By specialising the data and equations for a monad container distributive law to these, v_1 and v_2 become trivial (\text {pr}^A and \text {pr}^B are already trivial), and we are left with:

       \begin {align*}            u_1\ \iota ^A\ (\lambda  \_ . b) &= b\\     u_1\ a\ (\lambda  \_ . \iota ^B) &= \iota ^B\\     u_1\ (\sigma ^A\ a\ (\lambda  \_ . a'))\ (\lambda  \_ . b) &= u_1\ a\ (\lambda  \_ . u_1\ a'\ (\lambda  \_ . b))\\     u_1\ a\ (\lambda  \_ . \sigma ^B\ b\ (\lambda  \_ . b')) &= \sigma ^B\ (u_1\ a\ (\lambda  \_ . b))\ (\lambda  \_ . u_1\ (u_2\ a\ (\lambda  \_ . b)\ *)\ (\lambda  \_ . b'))\\      u_2\ \iota ^A\ (\lambda  \_ . b)\ * &= \iota ^A\\     u_2\ a\ (\lambda  \_ . \iota ^B)\ * &= a\\     u_2\ (\sigma ^A\ a\ (\lambda  \_ . a'))\ (\lambda  \_ . b)\ * &= \sigma ^A\ (u_2\ a\ (\lambda  \_ . u_1\ a'\ (\lambda  \_ . b))\ *)\ (\lambda  \_ . u_2\ a'\ (\lambda  \_ . b')\ *)\\     u_2\ a\ (\lambda  \_ . \sigma ^B\ b\ (\lambda  \_ . b'))\ * &= u_2\ (u_2\ a\ (\lambda  \_ . b)\ *)\ (\lambda  \_ . b')\ *        \end {align*}   

  Bear in mind that, since all position sets are 1, we do not lose generality by assuming constant all of the functions in the equations above. By defining:

       \begin {align*}            \alpha \ a\ b := u_1\ a\ (\lambda  \_ . b)\\     \beta \ a\ b := u_2\ a\ (\lambda  \_ . b)\ *\\     a \otimes ^A a' := \sigma ^A\ a\ (\lambda  \_ . a')\\     b \otimes ^B b' := \sigma ^B\ b\ (\lambda  \_ . b')        \end {align*}   

  we can rewrite these equations as:

       \begin {align*}            \alpha \ \iota ^A\ b &= b\\     \alpha \ a\ \iota ^B &= \iota ^B\\     \alpha \ (a \otimes ^A a')\ b &= \alpha \ a\ (\alpha \ a'\ b)\\     \alpha \ a\ (b \otimes ^B b') &= (\alpha \ a\ b) \otimes ^B (\alpha \ (\beta \ a\ b)\ b')\\      \beta \ \iota ^A\ b &= \iota ^A\\     \beta \ a\ \iota ^B &= a\\     \beta \ (a \otimes ^A a')\ b &= (\beta \ a\ (\alpha \ a'\ b)) \otimes ^A (\beta \ a'\ b')\\     \beta \ a\ (b \otimes ^B b') &= \beta \ (\beta \ a\ b)\ b'        \end {align*}   

  These are exactly the equations exhibiting \alpha  and \beta  as a matching pair of monoid actions between (A, \otimes ^A, \iota ^A) and (B , \otimes ^B, \iota ^B). Therefore, monad container distributive laws of this type are in bijection with matching pairs of actions for the relevant monoids.

Let (S \triangleright  P, \downarrow ^S, o^S, \oplus ^S) and (T \triangleright  Q, \downarrow ^T, o^T, \oplus ^T) be directed containers.
  A directed container distributive law [ahmanuustalu2013] of S \triangleright  P over T \triangleright  Q is given by the data:
       \begin {align*}       &u_2 : \prod _{s : S} \prod _{f : P\ s \to  T} Q\ (f\ o^S) \to  S\\       &v_1 : \prod _{\{s : S\}} \prod _{\{f : P\ s \to  T\}} \prod _{q : Q\ (f\ o^S)} P\ (u_2\ s\ f\ q) \to  P\ s\\       &v_2 : \prod _{\{s : S\}} \prod _{\{f : P\ s \to  T\}} \prod _{q : Q\ (f\ o^S)} \prod _{p : P\ (u_2\ s\ f\ q)} Q\ (f\ (v_1\ q\ p))\\     \end {align*}   
  where the following equalities hold:
       \begin {align*}       u_2\ s\ f\ q \downarrow ^S p &= u_2\ (s \downarrow ^S v_1\ q\ p)\ (\lambda  p' . f\ (v_1\ q\ p \oplus ^S p'))\ (v_2\ q\ p)\\       u_2\ s\ f\ o^T &= s\\       u_2\ s\ f\ (q \oplus ^T q') &= u_2\ (u_2\ s\ f\ q)\ (\lambda  p . f\ (v_1\ q\ p) \downarrow ^T v_2\ q\ p)\ q'\\       v_1\ q\ o^S &= o^S\\       v_1\ q\ (p \oplus ^S p') &= v_1\ q\ p \oplus ^S v_1\ (v_2\ q\ p)\ p'\\       v_1\ o^T\ p &= p\\       v_1\ (q \oplus ^T q')\ p &= v_1\ q\ (v_1\ q'\ p)\\       v_2\ q\ o^S &= q\\       v_2\ q\ (p \oplus ^S p') &= v_2\ (v_2\ q\ p)\ p'\\       v_2\ o^T\ p &= o^T\\       v_2\ (q \oplus ^T q')\ p &= v_2\ q\ (v_1\ q' p) \oplus ^T v_2\ q'\ p     \end {align*}

Let S \triangleright  P be a container. A directed container [ahmanchapmanuustalu2012] on S \triangleright  P is given by the following data:
       \begin {align*}       \downarrow  &: \prod _{s : S} P\ s \to  S\\       o &: \prod _{\{s : S\}} P\ s\\       \oplus  &: \prod _{\{s : S\}} \prod _{p : P\ s} P\ (s \downarrow  p) \to  P\ s     \end {align*}   
  satisfying two shape equations and three position equations:
       \begin {align*}       s \downarrow  o &= s\\       s \downarrow  (p \oplus  p') &= (s \downarrow  p) \downarrow  p'\\       p \oplus  o &= p\\       o \oplus  p &= p\\       (p \oplus  p') \oplus  p'' &= p \oplus  (p' \oplus  p'')     \end {align*}

Let (1 \triangleright  \lambda  \_ . A, \downarrow ^A, o^A, \oplus ^A) and (1 \triangleright  \lambda  \_ . B, \downarrow ^B, o^B, \oplus ^B) be representable directed containers. By specialising the equations of a directed container distributive law to these, all equations involving u_2 disappear and we are left with:
       \begin {align*}       v_1\ b\ o^A &= o^A\\       v_1\ o^B\ a &= a\\       v_1\ b\ (a \oplus ^A a') &= v_1\ b\ a \oplus ^A v_1\ (v_2\ b\ a)\ a'\\       v_1\ (b \oplus ^B b')\ a &= v_1\ b\ (v_1\ b'\ a)\\       v_2\ b\ o^A &= b\\       v_2\ o^B\ a &= o^B\\       v_2\ b\ (a \oplus ^A a') &= v_2\ (v_2\ b\ a)\ a'\\       v_2\ (b \oplus ^B b')\ a &= v_2\ b\ (v_1\ b' a) \oplus ^B v_2\ b'\ a     \end {align*}   
  which exhibit v_1 and v_2 as a matching pair of monoid maps between the monoids (A , o^A, \oplus ^A) and (B, o^B, \oplus ^B). Hence, directed container distributive laws of this type are in bijection with matching pairs of actions for the relevant monoids.

Let S \triangleright  P be a container. A lmf-container (lax-monoidal-functor-container) [uustalu2017] on S \triangleright  P is given by the following data:

       \begin {align*}            \iota  &: S\\     \otimes  &: S \to  S \to  S\\     \text {pr} &: \prod _{\{s : S\}} \prod _{\{s' : S\}} P\ (s \otimes  s') \to  P\ s \times  P\ s'        \end {align*}   

  satisfying the equations:

       \begin {align*}            s \otimes  \iota  &= s\\     \text {pr}_1\ p &= p\\     \iota  \otimes  s &= s\\     \text {pr}_2\ p &= p\\     (s \otimes  s') \otimes  s'' &= s \otimes  (s' \otimes  s'')\\     \text {pr}_1\ (\text {pr}_1\ p) &= \text {pr}_1\ p\\     \text {pr}_1\ (\text {pr}_2\ p) &= \text {pr}_2\ (\text {pr}_1\ p)\\     \text {pr}_2\ p &= \text {pr}_2\ (\text {pr}_2\ p)        \end {align*}   

  We abbreviate \pi _1 \circ  \text {pr} as \text {pr}_1 and \pi _2 \circ  \text {pr} as \text {pr}_2. Each set of laws for \text {pr} hold up to the laws for \oplus  above them.

Let (A \triangleright  \lambda  \_ . 1, \iota ^A, \sigma ^A, \text {pr}^A) and (B \triangleright  \lambda  \_ . 1, \iota ^B, \sigma ^B, \text {pr}^B) be monad containers. By specialising the data and equations for a monad container distributive law to these, v_1 and v_2 become trivial (\text {pr}^A and \text {pr}^B are already trivial), and we are left with:

       \begin {align*}            u_1\ \iota ^A\ (\lambda  \_ . b) &= b\\     u_1\ a\ (\lambda  \_ . \iota ^B) &= \iota ^B\\     u_1\ (\sigma ^A\ a\ (\lambda  \_ . a'))\ (\lambda  \_ . b) &= u_1\ a\ (\lambda  \_ . u_1\ a'\ (\lambda  \_ . b))\\     u_1\ a\ (\lambda  \_ . \sigma ^B\ b\ (\lambda  \_ . b')) &= \sigma ^B\ (u_1\ a\ (\lambda  \_ . b))\ (\lambda  \_ . u_1\ (u_2\ a\ (\lambda  \_ . b)\ *)\ (\lambda  \_ . b'))\\      u_2\ \iota ^A\ (\lambda  \_ . b)\ * &= \iota ^A\\     u_2\ a\ (\lambda  \_ . \iota ^B)\ * &= a\\     u_2\ (\sigma ^A\ a\ (\lambda  \_ . a'))\ (\lambda  \_ . b)\ * &= \sigma ^A\ (u_2\ a\ (\lambda  \_ . u_1\ a'\ (\lambda  \_ . b))\ *)\ (\lambda  \_ . u_2\ a'\ (\lambda  \_ . b')\ *)\\     u_2\ a\ (\lambda  \_ . \sigma ^B\ b\ (\lambda  \_ . b'))\ * &= u_2\ (u_2\ a\ (\lambda  \_ . b)\ *)\ (\lambda  \_ . b')\ *        \end {align*}   

  Bear in mind that, since all position sets are 1, we do not lose generality by assuming constant all of the functions in the equations above. By defining:

       \begin {align*}            \alpha \ a\ b := u_1\ a\ (\lambda  \_ . b)\\     \beta \ a\ b := u_2\ a\ (\lambda  \_ . b)\ *\\     a \otimes ^A a' := \sigma ^A\ a\ (\lambda  \_ . a')\\     b \otimes ^B b' := \sigma ^B\ b\ (\lambda  \_ . b')        \end {align*}   

  we can rewrite these equations as:

       \begin {align*}            \alpha \ \iota ^A\ b &= b\\     \alpha \ a\ \iota ^B &= \iota ^B\\     \alpha \ (a \otimes ^A a')\ b &= \alpha \ a\ (\alpha \ a'\ b)\\     \alpha \ a\ (b \otimes ^B b') &= (\alpha \ a\ b) \otimes ^B (\alpha \ (\beta \ a\ b)\ b')\\      \beta \ \iota ^A\ b &= \iota ^A\\     \beta \ a\ \iota ^B &= a\\     \beta \ (a \otimes ^A a')\ b &= (\beta \ a\ (\alpha \ a'\ b)) \otimes ^A (\beta \ a'\ b')\\     \beta \ a\ (b \otimes ^B b') &= \beta \ (\beta \ a\ b)\ b'        \end {align*}   

  These are exactly the equations exhibiting \alpha  and \beta  as a matching pair of monoid actions between (A, \otimes ^A, \iota ^A) and (B , \otimes ^B, \iota ^B). Therefore, monad container distributive laws of this type are in bijection with matching pairs of actions for the relevant monoids.

Given a monad container (S \triangleright  P, \iota , \sigma , \text {pr}), it's extension (see container extension) is the monad (\lbrack \negthinspace \lbrack  S \triangleright  P \rbrack \negthinspace \rbrack , \eta , \mu ) on \mathbf {Set} where

       \begin {align*}            \eta _A\ a &:= (\iota , \lambda  \_ . a)\\     \mu _A\ (s , f) &:= (\sigma \ s\ (\lambda  p . \pi _1\ (f\ p)) , \lambda  p' . \pi _2\ (f\ (\text {pr}_1\ p'))\ (\text {pr}_2\ p'))        \end {align*}   

  The diagrams for \eta  and \mu  commute given the equations of a monad container.

Let (1 \triangleright  \lambda  \_ . A, \downarrow ^A, o^A, \oplus ^A) and (1 \triangleright  \lambda  \_ . B, \downarrow ^B, o^B, \oplus ^B) be representable directed containers. By specialising the equations of a directed container distributive law to these, all equations involving u_2 disappear and we are left with:
