We write \mathcal {H}^- for the simple type environment satisfying:

x^+ : T \in  \mathcal {H}^- if and only if x^- : T \in  \mathcal {H}

x^- : T \in  \mathcal {H}^- if and only if x^+ : T \in  \mathcal {H}

x^\star  : T \in  \mathcal {H}^- if and only if x^\star  : T \in  \mathcal {H}

We write \mathcal {H}^- for the simple type environment satisfying:

x^+ : T \in  \mathcal {H}^- if and only if x^- : T \in  \mathcal {H}

x^- : T \in  \mathcal {H}^- if and only if x^+ : T \in  \mathcal {H}

x^\star  : T \in  \mathcal {H}^- if and only if x^\star  : T \in  \mathcal {H}

The State functor for some set of states S can be represented by the container S \to  S \triangleright  \lambda  \_ . S, which can be extended to a monad container with the data:
       \begin {align*}       \iota  &:= \lambda  x . x\\       \sigma \ f\ g &:= \lambda  s . g\ s\ (f\ s)\\       \text {pr}\ \{f\}\ \{g\}\ s &:= (s , f\ s)     \end {align*}   
  It is not cartesian for general S.

This is a central location for the core components and definitions of the \mu HOL^{ex} logic and cyclic proof system.
  527mhe-0005mhe-0005.xml\mu HOL^{ex} domain syntaxDefinition2024123Chris PurdyReuben Rowe
Domains/types in \mu HOL^{ex} are defined as follows, where D ranges over a countable set of base domains, and v ranges over the set \{+, -, \star \} of variance annotations.
       \begin {align*}       S, T &::= D\ |\ S \to ^v T\\       P &::= \text {Prop}\ |\ T \to ^v P     \end {align*}   
  The base domains would be specified in a signature.
  530mhe-0004mhe-0004.xml\mu HOL^{ex} formula syntaxDefinition2024123Chris Purdy
The syntax of \mu HOL^{ex} formulae has a small logical fragment, extended with a fixed-point operator, variance annotations [viswanathanviswanathan2004] and contraints for ordinal variables. v ranges over variance annotations, and P, T range over predicate and non-predicate domains respectively.
       t ::=\ x\ |\ \forall  (x : T).t\ |\ t \Rightarrow  t^\prime \ |\ \lambda (x^v : T).t\ |\ t\ t^\prime \ |\ \mu ^\alpha (x:P).t\ |\ \exists \alpha .t\ |\ \beta  < \alpha    
